<br>
1 "Do not judge lest you be judged.<br>
2 "For in the way you judge, you will be judged; and by your standard of measure, it will be measured to you.<br>
3 "And why do you look at the speck that is in your brother's eye, but do not notice the log that is in your own eye?<br>
4 "Or how can you say to your brother, 'Let me take the speck out of your eye,' and behold, the log is in your own eye?<br>
5 "You hypocrite, FIRST take the log out of your own eye, and THEN you will see clearly to take the speck out of your brother's eye.<br>
<br>
It is clear it is really telling you to be careful how you judge because you will be judged the same way.  If it truly meant to never judge then vs 5 wouldn't say FIRST remove your log THEN their speck.  I think the message is clear.<br>
<br>
<font color=yellow>You say, the Bible is his written word. That you have faith in that written record. But what makes your interpretation any closer to the actual words spoken by god than any other denomination's interpretation? Also, are you considering the textual bumps that go with the Bible where scribes have changed passages, translation problems from dead languages to current languages; and the fact that none of the original texts exist so there is no hope of being 100% certain that todays translations are exact copies of the Words of God? BTW, wouldn't you want that sort of certainty if your eternal soul is on the line? </font color><br>
<br>
There are several versions that differ in wording but not in the message.  I accept any of the NIV, NAS, KJV, NASB, LIV, etc.  There are scriptures that require interpretation.  When are images figurative and when are they literal.  There is no interpretation needed for a direct statement and several of the issues discussed are just that.. directly addressed.<br>
<br>
There are some very very old manuscripts of the Bible.  The Bible is a hard thing to change.  Being the most sold book on earth it would be hard to change key verses and not be found out.<br>
<br>
I am 100% certain, so that isn't an issue.  Lets just imagine for a second that the Bible doesn't say what it says... that baptism isn't essential... it wouldn't matter at all, because I would still be saved.  I still love.  I still attend church.  I still give.  I still believe.  etc, etc, etc.<br>
